children.subject: I would say a tutorial is closer to a small discussion with around 6-10 students. As a result, the responsibility of an AI would be slightly different (answering questions, leading breakout rooms to discuss tutorial problems, clarifying concepts etc.) than lab AIs in the past.
Hi is the tutorial just the equivalent of a smaller lab, i.e. the responsibility is the same as the AIs in labs?
From my end, I think I should be able to account for TA preferences if there are any.
Can we choose our TA if we know them well
The Google Form is the application! It is non-binding, so if you are accepted, then I will send out a follow-up form where you accept and commit to the AI role.
Is the google interest form the application? Or is there something else we need to do?
The plan is to send out the waves of results over the next couple days (likely most of them should be out before the end of Wednesday).
When will you send out the results?
The applications aren't evaluated on a rolling basis, but the results are being sent out in different waves. Ideally, all results will be sent out by Wednesday night.
Are applications evaluated on a rolling basis?

history.content:
Fact: Bears eat beets. Bears. Beets. Berkeley CS61A AI program is restarting this semester!

 

Hope you all had a relaxing winter break as we finished the last chapter of 2020! CS 61A’s Academic Intern program is restarting this upcoming semester, and the Spring 2021 interest form is now open. With the class growing every year, we’d love to have your help to continue scaling the class to support as many people as we can. 

 

If you're interested, then fill out this quick, non-binding interest form: https://forms.gle/jgv9uXivkvFWe2at9

 

AIs are former 61A students who help out in running the course. This semester, AIs will primarily help out in tutorials, a new teaching format instituted since school went online. In tutorials, course tutors will teach 6-10 students, and AIs will assist them in the tutorial (answering questions, leading breakout rooms etc.) Tutorials will be held on Wednesday after 4 PM and Thursday before 1 PM (all times in PST). We welcome anyone who has received a B or higher in CS 61A to be an academic intern.  

 

You will also have a TA as a mentor in our new “buddy” system, so feel free to ask them questions about best teaching practices, reinforcing concepts for students, and experiences about being a member of CS61A course staff and the CS teaching community as a whole!

 

Responsibilities include:

- 2 hours of teaching per week (must attend at least 80% of the tutorials) 

- 1 hour of prep time per week (includes a weekly assignment)

- Attend 61A AI Orientation on January 24th @ 7 PM PST

- Complete mid-semester survey

- Complete TA check-ins

- Keep an eye on Slack, which will be our primary method of communication (Slack invite will be sent after application results are sent out)

 

Couple of things to note:

  1. EECS department is requiring all academic interns to receive 1 P/NP unit for Academic Interning (CS 197) for 3 hours of work per week.

  2. Based on how we can best utilize Academic Interns in our Spring 2021 iteration of the course, there will, unfortunately, be far fewer spots available compared to past semesters. This is just the built-in limitation we have based on the way the course is designed.

 

The deadline to apply for the AI role is 1/18/2021. We will be sending out application results shortly after, along with the info about Slack and the AI Orientation! 

 

Please comment below with any general questions or email me at abhinav_ashar@berkeley.edu for any personal questions.
